We reported yesterday on extensive corruption within the South African Police Services. National Police Commissioner Khehla Sitole told the Standing Committee on Public told the Standing Committee on Public Accounts there have been 546 police members linked to 286 SAPS corruption cases. For more, Jeremy Maggs spoke to Scopa chair, Mkhuleko Hlengwa. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Parliament's Standing Committee on Public Accounts is calling for proper procedures to be followed to ensure corrupt police officials are brought to book. This comes after the National Police Commissioner, Khehla Sitole confirmed 546 police members were linked to corruption. READ: Police top of corruption charts, report finds "So for us, it is very clear that we are dealing with a situation and institution that has been infiltrated with corruption at various levels of leadership and management and lower ranks," said Scopa chairperson, Mkhuleko Hlengwa. Hlengwa says there is a history of corrupt officials who escape punishment.